Introduction {#sec1}
============

When confronted by a pathogen, the host's innate immune system is activated by pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) that recognize pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) ([@bib10]). For viruses, the detection of viral nucleic acids is a critical element of this recognition ([@bib46], [@bib60]). There are several intracellular DNA sensors, such as DNA-dependent activator of interferon (IFN)-regulatory factor (DAI) ([@bib72]), absent in melanoma 2 (AIM2) ([@bib12], [@bib18], [@bib25], [@bib33], [@bib62]), RNA polymerase III ([@bib1], [@bib15]), LRRFIP1 ([@bib79]), DExH-box helicase (DHX)9/DHX36 ([@bib40]), double-strand break repair protein MRE11 (MRE11) ([@bib42]), polyglutamine binding protein-1 (PQBP1) ([@bib80]), gamma-IFN inducible protein 16 (IFI16) ([@bib76]), cyclic guanosine monophosphate-AMP synthase (cGAS) ([@bib71]), and DNA-dependent protein kinase (DNA-PK) ([@bib24], [@bib81]).

